The issue with the current implementation is that it is only searching for the presence of the keywords "TABLE" and "COLUMNS" in the text. However, it is not considering the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns.

To address this issue, we can modify the function to analyze the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns. We can look for patterns such as rows of data with consistent column separators or headers for each column to identify a table or columns.

Let's update the function to implement this improved logic:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const headerRow = lines[1].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the second line by multiple spaces
    const dataRow = lines[2].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the third line by multiple spaces
    if (headerRow.length === dataRow.length) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

By analyzing the structure of the text data, we can determine whether it represents a table, columns, both, or neither based on the presence of consistent column separators and headers.

I see what went wrong in the previous function. The current logic checks for a consistent number of columns in the second and third lines to determine if it's a table. However, this approach is not reliable because the number of columns might not always be consistent in a text representation of a table.

To improve the function, I will update the logic to look for patterns that represent a table, such as the presence of multiple rows with consistent column structure and headers. Additionally, we will check for the presence of column separators and rows to determine the structure of the text.

Here's the updated function that incorporates these improvements:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n');

  // Check if the text represents a table
  let hasHeader = false;
  let hasSeparator = false;
  let hasData = false;

  for (let line of lines) {
    const columns = line.split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the line by multiple spaces

    if (columns.length > 1) {
      if (!hasHeader) {
        hasHeader = true;
      } else if (!hasSeparator && columns.every(cell => /[-]+/.test(cell))) {
        hasSeparator = true;
      } else if (hasHeader && !hasSeparator) {
        hasData = true;
      }
    }
  }

  if (hasHeader && hasSeparator && hasData) {
    return "TABLE";
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

This updated function analyzes the text for the presence of headers, separators, and data to determine if it represents a table. If the text contains these elements in the expected structure, it will be categorized as a table. If not, it will then be checked for the presence of columns. If neither a table nor columns are identified, the function will return "NORMAL". This approach provides a more robust determination of the text structure.
